If $$m = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$ and $$n = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$, then what is the value of the determinant of $$m\cos \theta $$ $$-$$ $$n\sin \theta $$ ?

explanation:
Given, $$m = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$ and $$n = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$m\cos \theta  = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$ and <br><br>$$n\sin \theta  = \left[ {\matrix{
   0 &amp; {\sin \theta }  \cr 
   { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$m\cos \theta  - n\sin \theta  = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta }  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Determinant of $$(m\cos \theta  - n\sin \theta ) = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta }  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta }  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = {\cos ^2}\theta  + {\sin ^2}\theta  = 1$$

