If $$f(x) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$, then which of the following are correct?<br><br>I. $$f(\theta ) \times f(\phi ) = f(\theta  + \phi )$$.<br><br>II. The value of the determinant of the matrix $$f(\theta ) \times f(\phi )$$ is 1.<br><br>III. The determinant of $$f(x)$$ is an even function.<br><br>Select the correct answer using the code given below.

explanation:
Given, <br><br>$$f(x) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$f(\theta ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta } &amp; { - \sin \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin \theta } &amp; {\cos \theta } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>and $$f(\phi ) = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \phi } &amp; { - \sin \phi } &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin \phi } &amp; {\cos \phi } &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$f(\theta ).f(\phi )$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos \theta .\cos \phi  - \sin \theta .\sin \phi  + 0} &amp; { - \cos \theta .\sin \phi  - \sin \theta .\cos \phi  + 0} &amp; {0 + 0 + 0}  \cr 
   {\sin \theta .\cos \phi  + \cos \theta .\sin \phi  + 0} &amp; { - \sin \theta .\sin \phi  + \cos \theta .\cos \phi  + 0} &amp; {0 + 0 + 0}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; {0 + 0 + 1}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = \left[ {\matrix{
   {\cos (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; { - \sin (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; {\cos (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$ = f(\theta  + \phi )$$<br><br>Now, determinant of $$f(\theta ) \times f(\phi )$$<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; { - \sin (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; {\cos (\theta  + \phi )} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = {\cos ^2}(\theta  + \phi ) + {\sin ^2}(\theta  + \phi ) = 1$$<br><br>Since, determinant of <br><br>$$f(x) = \left| {\matrix{
   {\cos x} &amp; { - \sin x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin x} &amp; {\cos x} &amp; 0  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = {\cos ^2}x + {\sin ^2}x = 1$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Determinant of f(x) is an even function.

Given equations are<br><br>$$x + y + z = 8$$ ....... (i)<br><br>$$x - y + 2z = 6$$ ...... (ii)<br><br>$$3x - y + 5z = k$$ ....... (iii)<br><br>Here, $$D = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 2  \cr 
   3 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 1( - 5 + 2) - 1(5 - 6) + 1( - 1 + 3)$$<br><br>$$ =  - 3 + 1 + 2 = 0$$<br><br>$${D_1} = \left| {\matrix{
   8 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   6 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 2  \cr 
   k &amp; { - 1} &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 8( - 5 + 2) - 1(30 - 2k) + 1( - 6 + k)$$<br><br>$$ =  - 24 - 30 + 2k - 6 + k$$<br><br>$$ = 3k - 60$$<br><br>$${D_2} = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 8 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 6 &amp; 2  \cr 
   3 &amp; k &amp; 5  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 1(30 - 2k) - 8(5 - 6) + 1(k - 18)$$<br><br>$$ = 30 - 2k - 40 + 48 + k - 18 = 20 - k$$<br><br>$${D_3} = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 8  \cr 
   1 &amp; { - 1} &amp; 6  \cr 
   3 &amp; { - 1} &amp; k  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 1( - k + 6) - 1(k - 18) + 8( - 1 + 3)$$<br><br>$$ =  - k + 6 - k + 18 + 15 = 40 - 2k$$<br><br>For, k = 15<br><br>D = 0 and D<sub>1</sub> $$\ne$$ 0, D<sub>2</sub> $$\ne$$ 0 and D<sub>3</sub> $$\ne$$ 0.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ No solution for k = 15.<br><br>For k = 20 $$\Rightarrow$$ D<sub>1</sub> = D<sub>2</sub> = D<sub>3</sub> = 0 and D = 0<br><br>$$\therefore$$ Infinitely many solution for k = 20.<br><br>Since, D = 0<br><br>$$\therefore$$ System have no unique solution for any value of k.

