Which of the following determinants have value 'zero'?<br><br>1. $$\left| {\matrix{
   {41} &amp; 1 &amp; 5  \cr 
   {79} &amp; 7 &amp; 9  \cr 
   {29} &amp; 5 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>2. $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; {b + c}  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {c + a}  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; {a + b}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>3. $$\left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; c &amp; b  \cr 
   { - c} &amp; 0 &amp; a  \cr 
   { - b} &amp; { - a} &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>Select the correct answer using the code given below.

explanation:
1. $$\left| {\matrix{
   {41} &amp; 1 &amp; 5  \cr 
   {79} &amp; 7 &amp; 9  \cr 
   {29} &amp; 5 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right| = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 5  \cr 
   7 &amp; 7 &amp; 9  \cr 
   5 &amp; 5 &amp; 3  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$[{C_1} \to {C_1} - 8{C_3}]$$<br><br>[$$\because$$ two columns of determinant are same, then value of determinant is zero.]<br><br>2. $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; {b + c}  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {c + a}  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; {a + b}  \cr 

 } } \right| = \left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; {a + b + c}  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {a + b + c}  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; {a + b + c}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$[{C_3} \to {C_2} + {C_3}]$$<br><br>$$ = (a + b + c)\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; a &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; c &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>[$$\because$$ two columns of determinant are same, then value of determinant is zero]<br><br>3. $$\left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; c &amp; b  \cr 
   { - c} &amp; 0 &amp; a  \cr 
   { - b} &amp; { - a} &amp; 0  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 0(0 + {a^2}) - c(0 + ab) + b(ac - 0)$$ [expanding with respect to R<sub>1</sub>]<br><br>$$ = 0 - c(ab) + b(ac) =  - abc + abc = 0$$<br><br>Hence, 1, 2, and 3 determinants have value 'zero'.

We have<br><br>kx + y + z = 1<br><br>x + ky + z = k<br><br>x + y + kz = k<sup>2</sup><br><br>For no solution $$\left| {\matrix{
   k &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; k &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; k  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow k({k^2} - 1) - 1(k - 1) + 1(1 - k) = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {k^3} - k - k + 1 + 1 - k = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {k^3} - 3k + 2 = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow (k + 2)(k - 1)(k - 1) = 0 \Rightarrow k = 1, - 2$$<br><br>But for k = 1, first two equations will be identical.<br><br>$$\therefore$$ k = $$-$$ 2

