If u, v and w (all positive) are the pth, qth, and rth terms of a GP, then the determinant of the matrix $$\left( {\matrix{
   {\ln \,u} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln v} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln w} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right)$$ is

explanation:
Given that u, v and w are the pth, qth and rth term of GP<br><br>$$\therefore$$ u = aR<sup>p $$-$$ 1</sup>, v = aR<sup>q $$-$$ 1</sup> [$$\because$$ a<sub>n</sub> = aR<sup>n $$-$$ 1</sup>] and w = aR<sup>r $$-$$ 1</sup>.<br><br>We have,<br><br>$$\left| {\matrix{
   {\ln \,u} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln v} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln w} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| = \left| {\matrix{
   {\ln \,a\,{R^{p - 1}}} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a\,{R^{q - 1}}} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a\,{R^{r - 1}}} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   {\ln a + (p - 1)\ln R} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a + (q - 1)\ln R} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a + (r - 1)\ln R} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   {\ln a} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {\ln a} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| + \left| {\matrix{
   {(p - 1)\ln R} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {(q - 1)\ln R} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {(r - 1)\ln R} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \ln a\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right| + \ln R\left| {\matrix{
   {p - 1} &amp; p &amp; 1  \cr 
   {q - 1} &amp; q &amp; 1  \cr 
   {r - 1} &amp; r &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = 0 + \ln R\left| {\matrix{
   {p - 1} &amp; {p - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   {q - 1} &amp; {q - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 
   {r - 1} &amp; {r - 1} &amp; 1  \cr 

 } } \right|$$ [$$\because$$ C<sub>1</sub> = C<sub>3</sub>]<br><br>= 0 [$$\because$$ C<sub>1</sub> = C<sub>2</sub>]

