If A, B and C are the angles of a triangle and $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   {1 + \sin A} &amp; {1 + \sin B} &amp; {1 + \sin C}  \cr 
   {\sin A + {{\sin }^2}A} &amp; {\sin B + {{\sin }^2}B} &amp; {\sin C + {{\sin }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$, then which one of the following is correct?

explanation:
We have,<br><br>$$\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   {1 + \sin A} &amp; {1 + \sin B} &amp; {1 + \sin C}  \cr 
   {\sin A + {{\sin }^2}A} &amp; {\sin B + {{\sin }^2}B} &amp; {\sin C + {{\sin }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right] = 0$$<br><br>R<sub>1</sub> $$\to$$ R<sub>1</sub> $$-$$ R<sub>2</sub>, R<sub>3</sub> $$\to$$ R<sub>3</sub> $$-$$ R<sub>2</sub><br><br>$$\left| {\matrix{
   { - \sin A} &amp; { - \sin B} &amp; { - \sin C}  \cr 
   {1 + \sin A} &amp; {1 + \sin B} &amp; {1 + \sin C}  \cr 
   {{{\sin }^2}A - 1} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}B - 1} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}C - 1}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>R<sub>2</sub> $$\to$$ R<sub>2</sub> + R<sub>1</sub><br><br>$$\left| {\matrix{
   { - \sin A} &amp; { - \sin B} &amp; { - \sin C}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   { - {{\cos }^2}A} &amp; { - {{\cos }^2}B} &amp; { - {{\cos }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>R<sub>3</sub> $$\to$$ R<sub>3</sub> + R<sub>2</sub><br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   {\sin A} &amp; {\sin B} &amp; {\sin C}  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   {{{\sin }^2}A} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}B} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>[C<sub>1</sub> $$\to$$ C<sub>1</sub> $$-$$ C<sub>2</sub>, C<sub>2</sub> $$\to$$ C<sub>2</sub> $$-$$ C<sub>3</sub>]<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow \left| {\matrix{
   {\sin A - \sin B} &amp; {\sin B - \sin C} &amp; {\sin C}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1  \cr 
   {{{\sin }^2}A - {{\sin }^2}B} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}B - {{\sin }^2}C} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow (\sin A - \sin B)(\sin B - \sin C)$$<br><br>$$\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; {\sin C}  \cr 
   0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0  \cr 
   {\sin A + \sin C} &amp; {\sin B + \sin C} &amp; {{{\sin }^2}C}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ sin A $$-$$ sin B = 0 or sin B $$-$$ sin C = 0<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ sin A = sin B and sin B = sin C<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ A = B and B = C<br><br>$$\therefore$$ A = B = C<br><br>Hence, triangle ABC is an equilateral.

